The reluctant hero
The most endearing thing about Aaron Green ‚Äì and there are many ‚Äì is his refusal to accept how famous he‚Äôs about to become. ‚ÄòI can walk down the street and not be hassled, which is really nice. I kind of hope that continues and I‚Äôm sure it will,‚Äô he says earnestly. He seems genuinely to believe that the job won‚Äôt change his life. ‚ÄòThere‚Äôs nothing fascinating about my life, and there‚Äôs absolutely no reason why that should start happening.‚Äô You can only wish him well.

How lovely if this turned out to be true, but the chances are it won‚Äôt, and he must know this. Aaron has been cast as the hero in the latest fantasy blockbuster that will hit our screens next year. The first photo of him in his costume was released last week to an Internet frenzy.

After an award nomination for his last film, Aaron is having the biggest year of his life, but it hasn‚Äôt gone to his head. ‚ÄòIt‚Äôs nice if your work is praised, but it‚Äôs all very new to me, this,‚Äô he says. ‚ÄòI really like working in this profession and exploring its possibilities. Who knows what the future holds? We could dream about what might happen next, but there‚Äôs not much point. I‚Äôm just enjoying my job and want to do well in it in the future, but that‚Äôs kind of it, really. No big hassles.‚Äô

Of all the characters in his last film, which is based on a true story about a group of university students who start an influential blog, Aaron‚Äôs character is the one who emerges as most likeable. But he insists that the plot is not as straightforward as it might appear. ‚ÄòWhat‚Äôs wonderful about this film is that everyone feels they are the good guy. I don‚Äôt think anyone in the cast felt they were playing the villain. It was just a group of human beings that had different opinions.‚Äô

It‚Äôs a typically thoughtful answer from the 27-year-old, who seems to be a bit of a worrier and prefers to avoid watching himself on screen. Doubtless he doesn‚Äôt care for interviews either, but he is so open and engaging that you wouldn‚Äôt know it. He felt ‚Äòa heightened sense of responsibility‚Äô playing a real-life person in his last film, but had no contact with the person concerned. ‚ÄòThese people are living and breathing somewhere ‚Äì of course that has a great effect on the care with which you approach your work. I kept wondering if he‚Äôd come and see the film, if he‚Äôd recognise himself in my performance or be angered by it.‚Äô

His performance has a vulnerability about it that is almost painful to watch. Does he seek out those parts or do directors see that quality in him? ‚ÄòI don‚Äôt know, I think it‚Äôs probably a bit of both. I certainly have that unwillingness to lose naivety; to lose that childlike way of looking at the world. I find it a very real and profound theme in my life and, talking to other people my age, I think it‚Äôs universal.

 In the first paragraph, the writer suggests that he thinks Aaron
answer_1: has a sensible attitude towards fame.
answer_2: seems confident that he can deal with fame.
answer_3: seems unaware that he‚Äôs about to become famous.
answer_4: has unrealistic ideas about what it‚Äôs like to be famous.

Melissa earns ¬£27,000 per year as the PA to a Sales Director at a large international company In London. She lives nearby in a flat she rents with her best friend, Sarah. The flat costs them ¬£450 per month each. Melissa is a likeable, bubbly person who is also known to be very good at her job.     Although she has a slight problem with punctuality and is sometimes forgetful, she is generally forgiven for her shortcomings because of her stylish dress sense and personality.
Melissa will be the first to admit, however, that her personal life is a complete disaster, especially on the financial front. She absolutely loves shopping and has accumulated, and used, a lot of credit cards. Everyone seemed to want to lend her money and she bought a car, went on holidays, furnished her flat and shopped till she dropped - all on borrowed money. On the shopping front, she reluctantly admits that being scatty and disorganised, she constantly buys things that she doesn't really need and never really thinks about what she spends her money on. She spends lots on cosmetics, shoes and clothes, but she has nothing to show for it because a lot of it is cheap junk. Massively in debt, Melissa avoids opening her bank or credit-card statements because the sight of them gets her down. She has no savings at all and frequently borrows money from her mum that she has no hope of paying back.
In the second paragraph, we learn that Melissa
answer_1: A makes some attempt to plan her spending.
answer_2: –í is unconcerned about her financial position.
answer_3: –° has been trying to economise in her shopping.
answer_4: D is aware that she may not always spend wisely.
subject: english

ask_text:
DESIGNER BRANDS ARE FOR MONKEYS
Even though I follow fashion (in a far from slavish way), there is no phrase that makes me recoil more than 'must-have'. If I read that X boots or the latest Y shades have been decreed to be the latest 'must-haves', my immediate reaction is mutiny. Why must I have them? Why should I humiliate myself to go on a waiting list for this supposedly desirable item? Most of all, why should I fall for the designer's manipulative tactics, which are intended only to swell his or her bank balance at the expense of mine? Far more satisfying is to pop into the clothes shops in my local mall and buy a copy of said designer's gear for a tenth of the price. Waiting lists? Huh! They're for mugs.
Actually, designer brands in general are for mugs. They are for people too insecure to trust their own taste. These people calculate that everything with a certain label must be cool, so shopping there is a safe bet. If you shop in the mall by contrast, you have to use your discernment to find the one garment out of three that looks great. If you go to a realty cheap shop, the ratio is more like one in 20. But boy is it worth it. Like spotting a little gold nugget in a muddy riverbed, the find gives rise to immense satisfaction. Which is why, according to a survey published this week, the young rich are deserting designer shops for second¬¨hand stores and flea-markets. They prefer to rummage for one-off bargains than to waste their money in some posh department store.

In this article, the writer is
answer_1: A questioning the quality of designer clothes.
answer_2: –í explaining the consequences of following fashion.
answer_3: –° encouraging people to develop their own taste in clothes.
answer_4: D reporting on ways to obtain designer clothes at good prices.
subject: english

ask_text:
CLICKING_THROUGH_A_MAG
For me, shopping is a social thing. It means time to gossip, drink coffee and keep up with friends and trends (and trends in friends). My consuming compatriots and I browse, select, try out for size and discuss - and only if the item is perfect do we buy. All of which is by way of explaining why I have never really understood the fascination with online shopping. Who wants to go it alone, sipping a mug of home-made coffee, buying items that you have never even touched, let alone tried on?
But it doesn't end there. Sitting alone, buying a ridiculously expensive item becomes strangely easier - you end up doing the kind of thing you'd never do in front of a friend who has shared your fears on the state of your credit card bill. True, online shopping avoids the pain of crowds, parking and sore feet but you miss out on the atmosphere and social stage, and you are, potentially at least, more vulnerable.

What does the writer imply by the phrase 'trends in friends'?
answer_1: A She worries about keeping up with a changing social scene.
answer_2: –í She doesn't place much importance on the opinions of others.
answer_3: –° She fears that her friends may be disloyal in her absence.
answer_4: D She doesn't meet her friends unless she goes shopping.
subject: english

ask_text:
Brick Lane
Thirty or so years after he arrived in London, Chanu decided that it was time to see the sights. ‚ÄúAll I saw was the Houses of Parliament. And that was in 1979.‚Äù It was a project. Much equipment was needed. Preparations were made. Chanu bought a pair of shorts which hung just below his knees. He tried them on and filled the numerous pockets with a compass, guidebook, binoculars, bottled water, maps and two types of disposable camera. Thus loaded, the shorts hung at mid-calf. He bought a baseball cap and wore it around the flat with the visor variously angled up and down and turned around to the back of his head. A money belt secured the shorts around his waist and prevented them from reaching his ankles. He made a list of tourist attractions and devised a star rating system that encompassed historical significance, something he termed ‚Äòentertainment factor‚Äô and value for money. The girls would enjoy themselves. They were forewarned of this requirement.

On a hot Saturday morning towards the end of July the planning came to fruition. ‚ÄúI‚Äôve spent more than half my life here,‚Äù said Chanu, ‚Äúbut I‚Äôve hardly left these few streets.‚Äù He stared out of the bus windows at the grimy colours of Bethnal Green Road. ‚ÄúAll this time I have been struggling and struggling, and I‚Äôve barely had time to lift my head and look around.‚Äù

They sat at the front of the bus, on the top deck. Chanu shared a seat with Nazneen, and Shahana and Bibi sat across the aisle. Nazneen crossed her ankles and tucked her feet beneath the seat to make way for the two plastic carrier bags that contained their picnic. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôll stink the bus out,‚Äù Shahana had said. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not sitting with you.‚Äù But she had not moved away.

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs like this,‚Äù said Chanu, ‚Äúwhen you have all the time in the world to see something, you don‚Äôt bother to see it. Now that we are going home, I have become a tourist‚Äù. He pulled his sunglasses from his forehead onto his nose. They were part of the new equipment.

He turned to the girls. ‚ÄúHow do you like your holiday so far?‚Äù Bibi said that she liked it very well, and Shahana squinted and shuffled and leaned her head against the side window.

Chanu began to hum. He danced with his head, which wobbled from side to side, and drummed out a rhythm on his thigh. The humming appeared to come from low down in his chest and melded with the general tune of the bus, vibrating on the bass notes.

Nazneen decided that she would make this day unlike any other. She would not allow this day to disappoint him.

The conductor came to collect fares. He had a slack-jawed expression: nothing could interest him. ‚ÄúTwo at one pound, and two children, please,‚Äù said Chanu. He received his tickets. ‚ÄúSightseeing,‚Äù he announced, and flourished his guidebook. ‚ÄúFamily holiday.‚Äù

‚ÄúRight,‚Äù said the conductor. He jingled his bag, looking for change. He was squashed by his job. The ceiling forced him to stoop.

‚ÄúCan you tell me something? To your mind, does the British Museum rate more highly than the National Gallery? Or would you recommend the gallery over the museum?‚Äù

The conductor pushed his lower lip out with his tongue. He stared hard at Chanu, as if considering whether to eject him from the bus.

‚ÄúIn my rating system,‚Äù explained Chanu, ‚Äúthey are neck and neck. It would be good to take an opinion from a local.‚Äù

‚ÄúWhere‚Äôve you come from, mate?‚Äù

‚ÄúOh, just two blocks behind,‚Äù said Chanu. ‚ÄúBut this is the first holiday for twenty or thirty years.‚Äù

The conductor swayed. It was still early but the bus was hot and Nazneen could smell his sweat. He looked at Chanu‚Äôs guidebook. He twisted round and looked at the girls. At a half-glance he knew everything about Nazneen, and then he shook his head and walked away.

In what sense was the sightseeing trip a ‚Äòproject‚Äô?
answer_1: Chanu felt a duty to do it.
answer_2: It was something that Chanu had wanted to do for a long time.
answer_4: It was something that required a good deal of organisation.
subject: english

answer_1: show how little he cared about his appearance.
answer_2: create an impression of his sense of humour.
answer_3: create amusing visual images of him.
answer_4: show how bad his choice of clothes always was.

How lovely if this turned out to be true, but the chances are it won‚Äôt, and he must know this. Aaron has been cast as the hero in the latest fantasy blockbuster that will hit our screens next year. The first photo of him in his costume was released last week to an Internet frenzy.

After an award nomination for his last film, Aaron is having the biggest year of his life, but it hasn‚Äôt gone to his head. ‚ÄòIt‚Äôs nice if your work is praised, but it‚Äôs all very new to me, this,‚Äô he says. ‚ÄòI really like working in this profession and exploring its possibilities. Who knows what the future holds? We could dream about what might happen next, but there‚Äôs not much point. I‚Äôm just enjoying my job and want to do well in it in the future, but that‚Äôs kind of it, really. No big hassles.‚Äô

Of all the characters in his last film, which is based on a true story about a group of university students who start an influential blog, Aaron‚Äôs character is the one who emerges as most likeable. But he insists that the plot is not as straightforward as it might appear. ‚ÄòWhat‚Äôs wonderful about this film is that everyone feels they are the good guy. I don‚Äôt think anyone in the cast felt they were playing the villain. It was just a group of human beings that had different opinions.‚Äô

It‚Äôs a typically thoughtful answer from the 27-year-old, who seems to be a bit of a worrier and prefers to avoid watching himself on screen. Doubtless he doesn‚Äôt care for interviews either, but he is so open and engaging that you wouldn‚Äôt know it. He felt ‚Äòa heightened sense of responsibility‚Äô playing a real-life person in his last film, but had no contact with the person concerned. ‚ÄòThese people are living and breathing somewhere ‚Äì of course that has a great effect on the care with which you approach your work. I kept wondering if he‚Äôd come and see the film, if he‚Äôd recognise himself in my performance or be angered by it.‚Äô

His performance has a vulnerability about it that is almost painful to watch. Does he seek out those parts or do directors see that quality in him? ‚ÄòI don‚Äôt know, I think it‚Äôs probably a bit of both. I certainly have that unwillingness to lose naivety; to lose that childlike way of looking at the world. I find it a very real and profound theme in my life and, talking to other people my age, I think it‚Äôs universal.

answer_1: has a sensible attitude towards fame.

CASE STUDY: MELISSA
Melissa earns ¬£27,000 per year as the PA to a Sales Director at a large international company In London. She lives nearby in a flat she rents with her best friend, Sarah. Although she has a slight problem with punctuality and is sometimes forgetful, she is generally forgiven for her shortcomings because of her stylish dress sense and personality.
Melissa will be the first to admit, however, that her personal life is a complete disaster, especially on the financial front. She absolutely loves shopping and has accumulated, and used, a lot of credit cards. Everyone seemed to want to lend her money and she bought a car, went on holidays, furnished her flat and shopped till she dropped - all on borrowed money. She spends lots on cosmetics, shoes and clothes, but she has nothing to show for it because a lot of it is cheap junk. Massively in debt, Melissa avoids opening her bank or credit-card statements because the sight of them gets her down. She has no savings at all and frequently borrows money from her mum that she has no hope of paying back.

answer_4: D maintaining the professional appearance demanded by her job.

ask_text:
DESIGNER BRANDS ARE FOR MONKEYS
Even though I follow fashion (in a far from slavish way), there is no phrase that makes me recoil more than 'must-have'. If I read that X boots or the latest Y shades have been decreed to be the latest 'must-haves', my immediate reaction is mutiny. Why must I have them? Why should I humiliate myself to go on a waiting list for this supposedly desirable item? Most of all, why should I fall for the designer's manipulative tactics, which are intended only to swell his or her bank balance at the expense of mine? Far more satisfying is to pop into the clothes shops in my local mall and buy a copy of said designer's gear for a tenth of the price. Waiting lists? Huh! They're for mugs.
Actually, designer brands in general are for mugs. They are for people too insecure to trust their own taste. These people calculate that everything with a certain label must be cool, so shopping there is a safe bet. If you shop in the mall by contrast, you have to use your discernment to find the one garment out of three that looks great. If you go to a realty cheap shop, the ratio is more like one in 20. But boy is it worth it. Like spotting a little gold nugget in a muddy riverbed, the find gives rise to immense satisfaction. Which is why, according to a survey published this week, the young rich are deserting designer shops for second¬¨hand stores and flea-markets. They prefer to rummage for one-off bargains than to waste their money in some posh department store.

In this article, the writer is
answer_1: A questioning the quality of designer clothes.
answer_2: –í explaining the consequences of following fashion.
answer_3: –° encouraging people to develop their own taste in clothes.
answer_4: D reporting on ways to obtain designer clothes at good prices.
subject: english

ask_text:
CLICKING_THROUGH_A_MAG
For me, shopping is a social thing. It means time to gossip, drink coffee and keep up with friends and trends (and trends in friends). My consuming compatriots and I browse, select, try out for size and discuss - and only if the item is perfect do we buy. All of which is by way of explaining why I have never really understood the fascination with online shopping. Who wants to go it alone, sipping a mug of home-made coffee, buying items that you have never even touched, let alone tried on?
But it doesn't end there. Sitting alone, buying a ridiculously expensive item becomes strangely easier - you end up doing the kind of thing you'd never do in front of a friend who has shared your fears on the state of your credit card bill. True, online shopping avoids the pain of crowds, parking and sore feet but you miss out on the atmosphere and social stage, and you are, potentially at least, more vulnerable.

What does the writer imply by the phrase 'trends in friends'?
answer_1: A She worries about keeping up with a changing social scene.
answer_2: –í She doesn't place much importance on the opinions of others.
answer_3: –° She fears that her friends may be disloyal in her absence.
answer_4: D She doesn't meet her friends unless she goes shopping.
subject: english

ask_text:
Brick Lane
Thirty or so years after he arrived in London, Chanu decided that it was time to see the sights. ‚ÄúAll I saw was the Houses of Parliament. And that was in 1979.‚Äù It was a project. Much equipment was needed. Preparations were made. Chanu bought a pair of shorts which hung just below his knees. He tried them on and filled the numerous pockets with a compass, guidebook, binoculars, bottled water, maps and two types of disposable camera. Thus loaded, the shorts hung at mid-calf. He bought a baseball cap and wore it around the flat with the visor variously angled up and down and turned around to the back of his head. A money belt secured the shorts around his waist and prevented them from reaching his ankles. He made a list of tourist attractions and devised a star rating system that encompassed historical significance, something he termed ‚Äòentertainment factor‚Äô and value for money. The girls would enjoy themselves. They were forewarned of this requirement.

On a hot Saturday morning towards the end of July the planning came to fruition. ‚ÄúI‚Äôve spent more than half my life here,‚Äù said Chanu, ‚Äúbut I‚Äôve hardly left these few streets.‚Äù He stared out of the bus windows at the grimy colours of Bethnal Green Road. ‚ÄúAll this time I have been struggling and struggling, and I‚Äôve barely had time to lift my head and look around.‚Äù

They sat at the front of the bus, on the top deck. Chanu shared a seat with Nazneen, and Shahana and Bibi sat across the aisle. Nazneen crossed her ankles and tucked her feet beneath the seat to make way for the two plastic carrier bags that contained their picnic. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôll stink the bus out,‚Äù Shahana had said. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not sitting with you.‚Äù But she had not moved away.

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs like this,‚Äù said Chanu, ‚Äúwhen you have all the time in the world to see something, you don‚Äôt bother to see it. Now that we are going home, I have become a tourist‚Äù. He pulled his sunglasses from his forehead onto his nose. They were part of the new equipment.

He turned to the girls. ‚ÄúHow do you like your holiday so far?‚Äù Bibi said that she liked it very well, and Shahana squinted and shuffled and leaned her head against the side window.

Chanu began to hum. He danced with his head, which wobbled from side to side, and drummed out a rhythm on his thigh. The humming appeared to come from low down in his chest and melded with the general tune of the bus, vibrating on the bass notes.

Nazneen decided that she would make this day unlike any other. She would not allow this day to disappoint him.

The conductor came to collect fares. He had a slack-jawed expression: nothing could interest him. ‚ÄúTwo at one pound, and two children, please,‚Äù said Chanu. He received his tickets. ‚ÄúSightseeing,‚Äù he announced, and flourished his guidebook. ‚ÄúFamily holiday.‚Äù

‚ÄúRight,‚Äù said the conductor. He jingled his bag, looking for change. He was squashed by his job. The ceiling forced him to stoop.

‚ÄúCan you tell me something? To your mind, does the British Museum rate more highly than the National Gallery? Or would you recommend the gallery over the museum?‚Äù

The conductor pushed his lower lip out with his tongue. He stared hard at Chanu, as if considering whether to eject him from the bus.

‚ÄúIn my rating system,‚Äù explained Chanu, ‚Äúthey are neck and neck. It would be good to take an opinion from a local.‚Äù

‚ÄúWhere‚Äôve you come from, mate?‚Äù

‚ÄúOh, just two blocks behind,‚Äù said Chanu. ‚ÄúBut this is the first holiday for twenty or thirty years.‚Äù

The conductor swayed. It was still early but the bus was hot and Nazneen could smell his sweat. He looked at Chanu‚Äôs guidebook. He twisted round and looked at the girls. At a half-glance he knew everything about Nazneen, and then he shook his head and walked away.

In what sense was the sightseeing trip a ‚Äòproject‚Äô?
answer_1: Chanu felt a duty to do it.
answer_2: It was something that Chanu had wanted to do for a long time.
answer_4: It was something that required a good deal of organisation.
subject: english
